multiprocessing plan

Based on the multiprocessing design document and current implementation status, here's a detailed description of each phase and todo item:

  Phase 1: File Discovery Operations ✅ COMPLETED

  Status: Fully implemented and tested
  Performance Target: 4-15x improvement for I/O bound operations

  Description: Parallelizes the fundamental file discovery operations that form the foundation of all analysis modes. These operations involve scanning directory structures to locate specific file types
  (.csproj, .cs, .sln files) across potentially large codebases.

  Implemented Functions:
  - find_files_with_pattern_parallel() - Core parallel file discovery with intelligent fallback
  - find_csproj_files() - Enhanced to use parallel discovery
  - find_cs_files_with_extensions() - Enhanced to use parallel discovery
  - find_changed_files() - Git branch analysis with parallel file operations

  Key Features:
  - Intelligent chunking strategy (75 directories per worker by default)
  - Automatic fallback to sequential processing for small directory sets
  - Configurable worker count and chunk sizes
  - 100% backwards compatibility with original function signatures
  - Comprehensive error handling and progress reporting

  ---
  Phase 2: Consumer Analysis 📋 PENDING - HIGH PRIORITY

  Performance Target: 3-8x improvement for project reference analysis

  Description: Parallelizes the core consumer analysis operations that determine which projects reference and use types from target projects. This is the most computationally intensive phase, involving XML
  parsing of .csproj files and text analysis of C# source files.

  Functions to Parallelize:
  - find_consumers_for_project() - Split project reference checking across workers
  - find_consumers_for_stored_procedure() - Parallelize stored procedure reference scanning
  - Enhanced project reference resolution with parallel XML parsing
  - Parallel namespace and class usage analysis across multiple .cs files

  Implementation Strategy:
  - Worker pools for .csproj file parsing and analysis
  - Parallel text processing for class/method usage detection
  - Chunked processing of consumer project candidates
  - Shared caching mechanisms for project metadata

  ---
  Phase 3: Reference Analysis 📋 PENDING - MEDIUM PRIORITY

  Performance Target: 2-5x improvement for dependency resolution

  Description: Parallelizes the detailed reference analysis operations that examine project-to-project relationships and using statement resolution. These operations involve parsing project files and
  analyzing import dependencies.

  Functions to Parallelize:
  - check_project_references() - Parallel scanning of ProjectReference elements in .csproj files
  - find_using_statements() - Parallel analysis of namespace imports across C# files
  - Solution file analysis for project relationship mapping
  - Dependency graph construction with parallel traversal

  Implementation Strategy:
  - Batch processing of .csproj files for reference extraction
  - Parallel using statement analysis across source files
  - Worker-based solution file parsing and relationship mapping

  ---
  Phase 4: Content Analysis 📋 PENDING - MEDIUM PRIORITY

  Performance Target: 2-4x improvement for source code analysis

  Description: Parallelizes the detailed source code content analysis operations that extract type declarations and search for specific class/method usage patterns. These are the most granular analysis
  operations.

  Functions to Parallelize:
  - find_class_usage() - Parallel text search for class references across multiple files
  - extract_class_declarations() - Parallel extraction of type definitions from C# source
  - Method usage analysis with parallel pattern matching
  - Parallel regex-based type declaration extraction

  Implementation Strategy:
  - Worker-based content scanning with regex pattern matching
  - Chunked processing of source files for usage analysis
  - Parallel type declaration extraction across multiple .cs files

